<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880511-0124 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides: Future Markets </HL><SO> </SO><TEXT>   When Robert A. Heinlein, one of science fiction's grandmasters, died this week an astonishing 64 of his books were still in print. An uncompromising individualist, Heinlein often celebrated the values of liberty and the free market in his work. He never pretended to write great literature; the acclaim he coveted most was that of the general reader. He once joked that &quot;the acme of prose style is exemplified by that simple, graceful clause: 'Pay to the order of . . .'&quot; </TEXT></DOC>